[normal]The Chairman:[bold] [bold]What is the Gover
[normal]nment’s position with regard to youth unemployment in the 
[normal]UK
[normal]?  What is the role of the devolved 
[normal]A
[normal]dministrations in tackling the issue?  You did relate to that up to a point.  Who would like to answer that question?
[normal]Lindsey Lewis[bold]: If I may, Chairman, I will start to answer and then I will ask my colleague Bill to follow.  While youth unemployment in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] is significantly lower than much of the rest of the EU, 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government believe that
[normal] this is still a significant issue that needs to be tackled.  Around 9% of 
[normal]16
[normal] to 
[normal]24 
[normal]year
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]olds are unemployed and not in full
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]time education; we think this is too high.
[normal]  This is why the Government have
[normal] implemented a range of policies to address this: those that Angus touched on, the Youth Contract
[normal],
[normal] and the Work Programme in particular.  
[normal]We are also reforming apprenticeships to create more opportunities for training via that route.  Our aim is to make our apprenticeship programme the new international benchmark for excellence.  We are seeing success.  For example, the number of 
[normal]16 to 24 year-old
[normal]s who are not employed or in full
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]time education fell by 7,000 in the last quarter and has fallen by 65,000 since the recent peak about two years ago.  I will ask my colleague Bill whether he wants to add anything.
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: It is quite important to distinguish between unemployment and other forms of worklessness.  Perhaps the best division is between those on 
[normal]jobseeker’s allowance
[normal], those on other benefits and those not on any other benefits.  In general, the story is that those on JSA are improving; those on other benefits—primarily lone parent and disability benefits—are at roughly the same level they were 
[normal]at 
[normal]before the recession.  The major problem tends to be 
[normal]people 
[normal]who are not on benefits and who are making the transition from education to work.  In our evidence, this is on chart
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.  These people have not 
[normal]yet 
[normal]moved
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] 
[normal]Yes
[normal], they have 
[normal]moved f
[normal]rom one to the other.  
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: It is important to realise that quite a lot of these people are not on benefits and are quite difficult to get hold of to help.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Why are they not on benefits?  It cannot be that they do not know benefits are available.
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: This is because it is 
[normal]16 to 24 year-old
[normal]s: 16 and 17
[normal] 
[normal]year
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]olds are not eligible for benefits.  Also, sometimes it takes a long time either to move into education or employment
[normal],
[normal] or to get involved in the benefits system.  That applies equall
[normal]y to people leaving university.
[normal]Over the last decade or so, it is taking longer for people who are leaving all forms of education to move into work.  In general, the story regarding the other two aspects that I mentioned—
[normal]jobseeker’s allowance
[normal] and other benefits—is very good compared 
[normal]with
[normal] the mass unemployment of the 1980s
[normal],
[normal] and as Lindsey said, for those on unemployment benefits there is now an improvement for those aged 18
[normal] to 
[normal]24.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] 
[normal]Could I ask a final question on that?  Have you done any work that gives you good evidence of how long it takes for somebody who, say, leaves school to actually 
[normal]get
[normal] a benefit?  I ask 
[normal]because 
[normal]there are an awful lot of scare stories in local newspapers at the moment.  The statement was made to me only yesterday that it takes 15
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]weeks for somebody to get a benefit.  If they are not living with their parents and have left school, this is really quite serious.  Do you have any idea about this?
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: The people from the DWP might want to add something to this, but there is a distinction between whether you are applying and then how long it takes you, once you have applied for it, to get the benefit.  The problem lies in 
[normal]the 
[normal]first of those, not the second, because Jobcentre
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Plus has targets for how quickly the benefits are paid.  
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] 
