[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Haskel:[bold] [bold]Mr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Wells told us about splitting up unemployed young people into three: people on 
[normal]jobseeker’s allowance
[normal], people on other benefits and people on no benefits.  Is there any further disaggregation necessary of the different types of young people and their different needs, so we can ensure the effectiveness of the policies?
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: Again, I probably have to distinguish between those on benefits and those not on benefits.  The focus of the work on people on benefits is individual
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]based; it is not based on their characteristics.  When they come in, there is a discussion with their advis
[normal]e
[normal]r, if it is Jobcentre
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Plus, as to the most effective way to get them into work.  There is a jobseeker’s agreement, which will take account of individual characteristics: for example, whether a lone parent 
[normal]needs
[normal] to have a certain work pattern.  However, the general policy of the 
[normal]UK
[normal] in this area is to focus on the individual and not to identify particular groups and treat 
[normal]them
[normal] as homogenous groups.
[normal]Lord Haskel:[bold] [bold]On the question of disaggregation, when we get the figures quoted they usually include full
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]time students.  You carefully disaggregated the full
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]time students.  How many full
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]time students are there?  What is the real figure?
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: I am not sure 
[normal]that 
[normal]I should say this is the real figure, but there are about 950,000 people on ILO unemployment and about 300,000 of those are in full
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]time education.  The improvement in ILO unemployment, although not substantia
[normal]l, has been greater than among
[normal] the ILO unemployed who are in full
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]time education.
[normal]Lord Haskel:[bold] [bold]Do you disaggregate the people as to their capabilities: for instance, into higher skills levels or higher academic levels?  Do you judge people and say, “He does not have much potential” or
[normal] 
[normal]“She does not have much potential”?
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: I will let my DWP colleagues talk about this a little.  It differs in different parts of the system.  If you 
[normal]are going in
[normal]to the Department for Work and Pensions, the disaggregation is based on the most effective way of getting them into work.  If you go through the education system, it is based on the best way to get them into education or the best way to get them into training.  From an employment perspective, which tends to be my background, the distinction is based on the most effective way of getting people into work.
[normal] 
[normal]Angus Gray[bold]: That is absolutely right: there is this individual diagnosis.  You would tend to give advice based on all sorts of things: ability, but also aspiration and motivation.  Often, the problem with young people is getting them 
[normal]focused
[normal] and interested.  At the beginning of entering the labour market, finding something that interests them and that they are capable of is as important as anything.
[normal]On your disaggregation point, the only thing I would add is that there is a bit of bias in the system around age.  There is a bias towards education and skills the younger they are in this group
[normal],
[normal] and there is a growing bias towards work as they get older.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] There is a big focus on NEETs. H
[normal]ow useful is it as a category?
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: It is slightly unfortunate that everybody collapses
[normal] it
[normal] into the word “NEETs”, because it is actually “not in education, employment or training”
[normal],
[normal] and so, for example, someone who leaves university and might be waiting to take up a job is included in the NEET figures.  This is a nightmare
[normal], given 
[normal]the different definitions in this area.
[normal]There are two definitions I would distinguish between, which might be helpful: one is unemployment, where people are looking for work; the other one is what I call economic inactivity, which is where someone is outside the labour market and not looking for work.  The workless include both those groups.  The problem tends to be, as I 
[normal]intimated
[normal] before, among
[normal] the people who are not looking for work and not looking for education either.  It is the workless people who are regarded in the labour
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]market statistics as not looking for work, where the structural problem in youth worklessness
[normal], 
[normal]as I would call it
[normal], 
[normal]has grown over time.  If you do not look for work, you will not get a job.
[normal]Angus Gray[bold]: Bill’s analysis of the numbers is absolutely right.  However, you can look beyond the numbers at some of the people we worry about.  This is my own word association, but when I think about NEETs I think about some of the most disadvantaged young people.  At the 
[normal]younger ages, you
[normal] might think of persistent truants and people who have chaotic lifestyles at home.  You need to find them first, but the focus on them is absolutely crucial, because we are trying to avoid them losing
[normal]—
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] 
[normal]T
[normal]he ability to work.
[normal]Angus Gray[bold]:
[normal] Yes.
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: To pick that up, part of the story is that there is a greater focus within the system on the most disadvantaged people.  One of those elements is how long they have been in that situation.  The long
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term unemployed would receive more direct help from Jobcentre
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Plus, whereas the expectation is that you get the short
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]term unemployed to look for work effectively and most of them will find that job within not very long at all.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] A lot of these people come from homes where people have never worked; there is no tradition of working.  There is 
[normal]more 
[normal]a tradition of, “Well, we will just g
[normal]et
[normal] by
[normal]. T
[normal]here is
[normal] nothing 
[normal]we are skilled for”
[normal]— 
[normal]depression really
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]Is that true?  We hear a lot of stories about that.  Again, this could just be anecdotal.
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: It is overstated.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Is it?  I see.
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: It may be that the numbers do not tell the whole story, but if you look at the stories about two or three generations where nobody has worked, from what we can tell the numbers are quite small.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Do you have any actual evidence of that or numbers you could quote us?  It would be great if we could actually make that point in our final report.
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: Yes, we do.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Do not worry about it now, but we would be grateful if you could send it to us.
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: Yes, of course.
[normal]Angus Gray[bold]: My understanding is that Bill is absolutely right, but you do get families and communities and where there is very little work.  Never having worked is quite a high bar.  You might have done the odd week or two
[normal],
[normal] and then you are not in the “never worked” category.
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: 
[normal]T
[normal]he concentration of worklessness 
[normal]may be 
[normal]an issue, rather than the history of worklessness.
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Fearn:[bold] To what extent is the Government’s position on youth unemployment influenced by EU policy?  How are EU actions to tackle youth unemployment generally being interpreted and delivered in the 
[normal]UK
[normal]?
[normal]Lindsey Lewis[bold]: 
[normal]My 
[normal]Lord Chairman, employment policy remains a 
[normal]member state
[normal] competence, but we do value the opportunity given by the European
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]s
[normal]emester to share experiences with other 
[normal]member state
[normal]s.  For example, we are sending a 
[normal]UK
[normal] official to a mutual
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]learning event in the 
[normal]Netherlands
[normal] in November and we are holding a mutual
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]learning event here on the minimum wage in April next year.  We will take part in multilateral surveillance, as part of the European
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]s
[normal]emester process, where we will be challenge
[normal]d
[normal] on our performance in this area and we have the opportunity to challenge others.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] It is a useful function, is it not?
[normal]Lindsey Lewis[bold]: I believe so, yes.
[normal]Lord Fearn:[bold] When this deputation goes, are they going with 
[normal]UK
[normal] policy on the unemployed?
[normal]Lindsey Lewis[bold]: The people who are going are policy officials, who are responsible for developing our policy.  It should inform policy development going forward.
[normal]Lord Fearn:[bold] What 
[normal]is the backup from 
[normal]that?  Where does it go after that, when they get back from 
[normal]Holland
[normal]?
[normal]Lindsey Lewis[bold]: It informs the policy process.  It is an opportunity to learn about a number of other countries’ policies and the way things work in their systems and to feed that into policy development in the 
[normal]UK
[normal].  There is no formal product, but it then becomes part of our knowledge base and our understanding.
[normal]Bill Wells[bold]: There is an important point about how most different countries have different systems.  Therefore, it is not a case of, say, going to the 
[normal]Netherlands
[normal],
[normal] seeing the system and importing it wholesale over here.  The good ideas of things that seem to work are purloined by us and put alongside ours to see whether we could develop the policy in ways that suit the 
[normal]UK
[normal] system.  Particularly in the employment field, the labour markets tend to be quite different in many of the 
[normal]member state
[normal]s.
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Wilson of Tillyorn:[bold] What I was going to ask follows on from that and
[normal] from what 
[normal]Mr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Gray said at the beginning about the EU’s Youth
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Employment
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Initiative, which has the rather odd acronym of YEI.  How does that tie in with our own policies?  Let us divide it up, if you would, into the 
[normal]youth
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]guarantee 
[normal]scheme, European
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]alliance for apprenticeships and the quality framework for traineeship
[normal]s.  Taking that last one, I notice that the paper from
[normal] the
[normal] Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, which I thought was very good, said about traineeship
[normal]s
[normal] that if some of the Commission’s proposals were taken into account it would not 
[normal]actually 
[normal]produc
[normal]e
[normal] the right sort of answers; it would do exactly the opposite.  Could you deal with these three different categories?
[normal]Angus Gray[bold]: To start with the overall bit about the YEI, the good news is that it is an additional source of funding, rather than a set of activities.  Because it fits within the European
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Social
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fund framework more generally, it is for 
[normal]member state
[normal]s to 
[normal]design
[normal] what they are going to do with the allocation.  That very much leaves us free to design interventions 
[normal]that
[normal] we think are appropriate for our context.  However, probably most importantly in 
[normal]England
[normal], the challenge for the European
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Social
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fund is always to add value to what already exists.  In some of the EU 
[normal]member state
[normal]s, the structural
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]funds investment is either the only thing or by far the biggest thing that happens in their country on these topics, whereas we already have substantial investment of all sorts.  Therefore, what you need to do is make sure ESF is filling the gaps.
[normal]We have seen this with some of the strategies that have come back
[normal]. O
[normal]ften, one of the things ESF can helpfully be used for is preparing people so they are ready for other mainstream provision
[normal], 
[normal]if that makes sense.  If they are some of the most disadvantaged, finding and equipping them so they are more likely to benefit from a traineeship or an apprenticeship is one of the key added
